Issues.Body:
### System information

- **OS version/distro**: Windows
- **.NET Version (eg., dotnet --info)**:  .NET Core 2.1

### Issue

- **What did you do?**
Load the model and call `CreatePredictionEngine` on a pipeline that was created like this:

```C#
            var ml = new MLContext(seed: 1);
            var data = ml.Data.LoadFromTextFile<SentimentData>(GetDataPath(TestDatasets.Sentiment.trainFilename), hasHeader: true);

            // Pipeline.
            var pipeline = ml.Transforms.Text.FeaturizeText("Features", "SentimentText")
                .AppendCacheCheckpoint(ml)
                .Append(ml.BinaryClassification.Trainers.SdcaNonCalibrated(
                    new SdcaNonCalibratedBinaryTrainer.Options { NumberOfThreads = 1 }));

            // Train.
            var model = pipeline.Fit(data);

            var modelPath = GetOutputPath("temp.zip");
            // Save model. 
            ml.Model.Save(model, data.Schema, modelPath);

            // Load model.
            var loadedModel = ml.Model.Load(modelPath, out var inputSchema);

            // Create prediction engine and test predictions.
            var engine = ml.Model.CreatePredictionEngine<SentimentData, SentimentPrediction>(loadedModel, inputSchema);
```

- **What happened?**
It takes an incredible amount of time to `CreatePredictionEngine`. Using the attached model.zip
[SentimentModel.zip](https://github.com/dotnet/machinelearning/files/3015931/SentimentModel.zip) it takes roughly 1.5 seconds for `CreatePredictionEngine` on my machine in a benchmark:

|                 Method |    Mean |    Error |   StdDev | Gen 0/1k Op | Gen 1/1k Op | Gen 2/1k Op | Allocated Memory/Op |
|----------------------- |--------:|---------:|---------:|------------:|------------:|------------:|--------------------:|
| CreatePredictionEngine | 1.516 s | 0.0302 s | 0.0461 s |  14000.0000 |   6000.0000 |           - |           146.35 MB |

- **What did you expect?**
I expected the model to load in a much shorter time with a lot less memory being allocated.

### Source code / logs

Doing a profile of the [Benchmark](https://github.com/glennc/Extensions.ML/blob/840211d64e1e165a124fd17020339479aac79231/benchmarks/micro/CreationBenchmarks.cs#L25-L29), I was able to get this flame graph:

![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/8291187/55124572-aa2ee680-50d4-11e9-8d5e-92fe5dc0846e.png)

As you can see, the two boxes show where we are writing a model and compressing it twice, just during the call to `CreatePredictionEngine`. This is because of the following code:

https://github.com/dotnet/machinelearning/blob/beb67a128544ee98b8c4309859f7e5a9f679ac4e/src/Microsoft.ML.Transforms/Text/TextFeaturizingEstimator.cs#L663-L679

Here, `TextFeaturizingEstimator.Transformer` is doing things the "old way" using `ApplyTransformUtils.ApplyAllTransformsToData`, which operates on `IDataTransform`s. This eventually gets into:

https://github.com/dotnet/machinelearning/blob/70ef7ecd43b031b481a4047ea361da5e2f360336/src/Microsoft.ML.Data/Utilities/ApplyTransformUtils.cs#L35-L52

which is serializing and deserializing the transform, which is super expensive.

This happens twice because once inside `GetRowToRowMapper` and once inside `GetOutputSchema`.

We should optimize the text featurizing transform so creating a prediction engine isn't so slow.

